# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mechanism-design
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mechanism-design/incentive-compatibility] In game theory and economics, a mechanism is called **incentive-compatible** (**IC**) if every participant can achieve their own best outcome by reporting their true preferences.
[src:mechanism-design/incentive-compatibility] For example, there is incentive compatibility if high-risk clients are better off in identifying themselves as high-risk to insurance firms, who only sell discounted insurance to high-risk clients.
[src:mechanism-design/incentive-compatibility] Likewise, they would be worse off if they pretend to be low-risk.
[src:mechanism-design/incentive-compatibility] Low-risk clients who pretend to be high-risk would also be worse off.
[src:mechanism-design/incentive-compatibility] The concept is attributed to the Russian-born American economist Leonid Hurwicz.
[src:mechanism-design/incentive-compatibility] Every DSIC mechanism is also BNIC, but a BNIC mechanism may exist even if no DSIC mechanism exists.
[src:mechanism-design/incentive-compatibility] Typical examples of DSIC mechanisms are second-price auctions and a simple majority vote between two choices.
[src:mechanism-design/incentive-compatibility] Typical examples of non-DSIC mechanisms are ranked voting with three or more alternatives (by the Gibbard–Satterthwaite theorem) or first-price auctions.
[src:mechanism-design/incentive-compatibility] A randomized mechanism is a probability-distribution on deterministic mechanisms.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Mechanism design has broad applications, including traditional domains of economics such as market design, but also political science (through voting theory).
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] It is a foundational component in the operation of the internet, being used in networked systems (such as inter-domain routing), e-commerce, and advertisement auctions by Facebook and Google.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Because it starts with the end of the game (a particular result), then works backwards to find a game that implements it, it is sometimes described as **reverse game theory**.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Leonid Hurwicz explains that "in a design problem, the goal function is the main given, while the mechanism is the unknown.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] The 2007 Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences was awarded to Leonid Hurwicz, Eric Maskin, and Roger Myerson "for having laid the foundations of mechanism design theory." The related works of William Vickrey that established the field earned him the 1996 Nobel prize.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] One person, called the "principal", would like to condition his behavior on information privately known to the players of a game.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] For example, the principal would like to know the true quality of a used car a salesman is pitching.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] He cannot learn anything simply by asking the salesman, because it is in the salesman's interest to distort the truth.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] However, in mechanism design, the principal does have one advantage: He may design a game whose rules influence others to act the way he would like.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Without mechanism design theory, the principal's problem would be difficult to solve.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] He would have to consider all the possible games and choose the one that best influences other players' tactics.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] In addition, the principal would have to draw conclusions from agents who may lie to him.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Thanks to the revelation principle, the principal only needs to consider games in which agents truthfully report their private information.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Mechanism design has been described by Noam Nisan as a way to escape the Gibbard–Satterthwaite theorem.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] While the theorem is traditionally presented as a result about voting systems, it can also be seen as an important result of mechanism design, which deals with a broader class of decision rules.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] The main idea of these "escape routes" is to modify a model to allow for a broader class of mechanisms, similar to the escape routes from Arrow's impossibility theorem in the case of ranked voting.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] A game of mechanism design is a game of private information in which one of the agents, called the principal, chooses the payoff structure.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Following Harsanyi (1967), the agents receive secret "messages" from nature containing information relevant to payoffs.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] For example, a message may contain information about their preferences or the quality of a good for sale.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] We call this information the agent's "type" (usually noted $\theta$ and accordingly the space of types $\Theta$ ).
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Agents then report a type to the principal (usually noted with a hat ${\hat {\theta }}$ ) that can be a strategic lie.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] After the report, the principal and the agents are paid according to the payoff structure the principal chose.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] As a benchmark the designer often defines what should happen under full information.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] A proposed mechanism constitutes a Bayesian game (a game of private information), and if it is well-behaved the game has a Bayesian Nash equilibrium.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] It is difficult to solve for Bayesian equilibria in such a setting because it involves solving for agents' best-response strategies and for the best inference from a possible strategic lie.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Thanks to a sweeping result called the revelation principle, no matter the mechanism a designer can confine attention to equilibria in which agents truthfully report type.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] The principle allows one to solve for a Bayesian equilibrium by assuming all players truthfully report type (subject to an incentive compatibility constraint).
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] In one blow it eliminates the need to consider either strategic behavior or lying.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Assume a Bayesian game in which the agent's strategy and payoff are functions of its type and what others do, $u_{i}\left(s_{i}(\theta _{i}),s_{-i}(\theta _{-i}),\theta _{i}\right)$ .
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Simply define a mechanism that would induce agents to choose the same equilibrium.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] The easiest one to define is for the mechanism to commit to playing the agents' equilibrium strategies *for* them.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Under such a mechanism the agents of course find it optimal to reveal type since the mechanism plays the strategies they found optimal anyway.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] To **implement** a social choice function $f(\theta )$ is to find some transfer function $t(\theta )$ that motivates agents to pick $f(\theta )$ .
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] we say the mechanism implements the social choice function.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Thanks to the revelation principle, the designer can usually find a transfer function $t(\theta )$ to implement a social choice by solving an associated truthtelling game.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] we say such a mechanism is **truthfully implementable**.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] The task is then to solve for a truthfully implementable $t(\theta )$ and impute this transfer function to the original game.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] which is also called the **incentive compatibility** (IC) constraint.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] In applications, the IC condition is the key to describing the shape of $t(\theta )$ in any useful way.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Under certain conditions it can even isolate the transfer function analytically.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Additionally, a participation (individual rationality) constraint is sometimes added if agents have the option of not playing.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Consider a setting in which all agents have a type-contingent utility function $u(x,t,\theta )$ .
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Consider also a goods allocation $x(\theta )$ that is vector-valued and size k (which permits k number of goods) and assume it is piecewise continuous with respect to its arguments.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] whenever $x=x(\theta )$ and $t=t(\theta )$ and *x* is continuous at $\theta$ .
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] This is a necessary condition and is derived from the first- and second-order conditions of the agent's optimization problem assuming truth-telling.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Its meaning can be understood in two pieces.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] In short, agents will not tell the truth if the mechanism does not offer higher agent types a better deal.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Otherwise, higher types facing any mechanism that punishes high types for reporting will lie and declare they are lower types, violating the truthtelling incentive-compatibility constraint.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] which, to be positive, means higher types must be given more of the good.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] There is potential for the two pieces to interact.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] If for some type range the contract offered less quantity to higher types $\partial x/\partial \theta <0$ , it is possible the mechanism could compensate by giving higher types a discount.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] But such a contract already exists for low-type agents, so this solution is pathological.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Such a solution sometimes occurs in the process of solving for a mechanism.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] In a multiple-good environment it is also possible for the designer to reward the agent with more of one good to substitute for less of another (e.g. butter for margarine).
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Multiple-good mechanisms are an area of continuing research in mechanism design.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] This is known by several names: the single-crossing condition, the sorting condition and the Spence–Mirrlees condition.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] It means the utility function is of such a shape that the agent's MRS is increasing in type.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] This is a technical condition bounding the rate of growth of the MRS.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] These assumptions are sufficient to provide that any monotonic $x(\theta )$ is implementable (a $t(\theta )$ exists that can implement it).
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] In addition, in the single-good setting the single-crossing condition is sufficient to provide that only a monotonic $x(\theta )$ is implementable, so the designer can confine his search to a monotonic $x(\theta )$ .
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Vickrey (1961) gives a celebrated result that any member of a large class of auctions assures the seller of the same expected revenue and that the expected revenue is the best the seller can do.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] The last condition is crucial to the theorem.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] An implication is that for the seller to achieve higher revenue he must take a chance on giving the item to an agent with a lower valuation.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Usually this means he must risk not selling the item at all.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] The Vickrey (1961) auction model was later expanded by Clarke (1971) and Groves to treat a public choice problem in which a public project's cost is borne by all agents, e.g. whether to build a municipal bridge.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] The resulting "Vickrey–Clarke–Groves" mechanism can motivate agents to choose the socially efficient allocation of the public good even if agents have privately known valuations.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] In other words, it can solve the "tragedy of the commons"—under certain conditions, in particular quasilinear utility or if budget balance is not required.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Consider a setting in which I number of agents have quasilinear utility with private valuations $v(x,t,\theta )$ where the currency t is valued linearly.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] The cleverness of the VCG mechanism is the way it motivates truthful revelation.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] It eliminates incentives to misreport by penalizing any agent by the cost of the distortion he causes.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Among the reports the agent may make, the VCG mechanism permits a "null" report saying he is indifferent to the public good and cares only about the money transfer.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] This effectively removes the agent from the game.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] If an agent does choose to report a type, the VCG mechanism charges the agent a fee if his report is **pivotal**, that is if his report changes the optimal allocation *x* so as to harm other agents.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] which sums the distortion in the utilities of the other agents (and not his own) caused by one agent reporting.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Gibbard (1973) and Satterthwaite (1975) give an impossibility result similar in spirit to Arrow's impossibility theorem.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] For a very general class of games, only "dictatorial" social choice functions can be implemented.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Myerson and Satterthwaite (1983) show there is no efficient way for two parties to trade a good when they each have secret and probabilistically varying valuations for it, without the risk of forcing one party to trade at a loss.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] It is among the most remarkable negative results in economics—a kind of negative mirror to the fundamental theorems of welfare economics.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] A symmetrical statement is similarly valid for utility-sharing games with convex utility functions.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Mirrlees (1971) introduces a setting in which the transfer function *t*() is easy to solve for.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Due to its relevance and tractability it is a common setting in the literature.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] and in which the principal has a prior CDF over the agent's type $P(\theta )$ .
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] The principal here is a monopolist trying to set a profit-maximizing price scheme in which it cannot identify the type of the customer.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] A common example is an airline setting fares for business, leisure and student travelers.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Due to the IR condition it has to give every type a good enough deal to induce participation.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Due to the IC condition it has to give every type a good enough deal that the type prefers its deal to that of any other.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] This function can be maximized pointwise.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Because $U(\theta )$ is incentive-compatible already the designer can drop the IC constraint.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] If the utility function satisfies the Spence–Mirrlees condition then a monotonic $x(\theta )$ function exists.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] The IR constraint can be checked at equilibrium and the fee schedule raised or lowered accordingly.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Additionally, note the presence of a hazard rate in the expression.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] If the type distribution bears the monotone hazard ratio property, the FOC is sufficient to solve for *t*().
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] If not, then it is necessary to check whether the monotonicity constraint (see sufficiency, above) is satisfied everywhere along the allocation and fee schedules.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] If not, then the designer must use Myerson ironing.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] In some applications the designer may solve the first-order conditions for the price and allocation schedules yet find they are not monotonic.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] For example, in the quasilinear setting this often happens when the hazard ratio is itself not monotone.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] By the Spence–Mirrlees condition the optimal price and allocation schedules must be monotonic, so the designer must eliminate any interval over which the schedule changes direction by flattening it.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Intuitively, what is going on is the designer finds it optimal to **bunch** certain types together and give them the same contract.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Normally the designer motivates higher types to distinguish themselves by giving them a better deal.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] If there are insufficiently few higher types on the margin the designer does not find it worthwhile to grant lower types a concession (called their information rent) in order to charge higher types a type-specific contract.
[src:mechanism-design/mechanism-design] Consider a monopolist principal selling to agents with quasilinear utility, the example above.
