[src:mechanism-design/revelation-principle] The **revelation principle** is a fundamental result in mechanism design, social choice theory, and game theory which shows it is always possible to design a strategy-resistant implementation of a social decision-making mechanism (such as an electoral system or market).
[src:mechanism-design/revelation-principle] It can be seen as a kind of mirror image to Gibbard's theorem.
[src:mechanism-design/revelation-principle] The revelation principle says that if a social choice function can be implemented with some non-honest mechanism—one where players have an incentive to lie—the same function can be implemented by an incentive-compatible (honesty-promoting) mechanism with the same equilibrium outcome (payoffs).
[src:mechanism-design/revelation-principle] The idea behind the revelation principle is that, if we know which strategy the players in a game will use, we can simply ask all the players to submit their true payoffs or utility functions; then, we take those preferences and calculate each voter's optimal strategy before executing it for them.
[src:mechanism-design/revelation-principle] This procedure means that an honest report of preferences is now the best-possible strategy, because it guarantees the mechanism will play the optimal strategy for the player.
[src:mechanism-design/revelation-principle] There is a certain item that Alice values as $v_{A}$ and Bob values as $v_{B}$ .
[src:mechanism-design/revelation-principle] The government needs to decide who will receive that item and in what terms.
[src:mechanism-design/revelation-principle] Suppose we have an arbitrary mechanism **Mech** that implements **Soc**.
[src:mechanism-design/revelation-principle] We construct a direct mechanism **Mech'** that is truthful and implements **Soc**.
[src:mechanism-design/revelation-principle] Reporting the true valuations in **Mech'** is like playing the equilibrium strategies in **Mech**.
[src:mechanism-design/revelation-principle] Hence, reporting the true valuations is a Nash equilibrium in **Mech'**, as desired.
[src:mechanism-design/revelation-principle] Moreover, the equilibrium payoffs are the same, as desired.
[src:mechanism-design/revelation-principle] In mechanism design, the revelation principle is importance in finding solutions.
[src:mechanism-design/revelation-principle] The researcher need only look at the set of equilibria characterized by incentive compatibility.
[src:mechanism-design/revelation-principle] That is, if the mechanism designer wants to implement some outcome or property, they can restrict their search to mechanisms in which agents are willing to reveal their private information to the mechanism designer that has that outcome or property.
[src:mechanism-design/revelation-principle] If no such direct and truthful mechanism exists, no mechanism can implement this outcome by contraposition.
[src:mechanism-design/revelation-principle] By narrowing the area needed to be searched, the problem of finding a mechanism becomes much easier.
[src:mechanism-design/revelation-principle] The revelation principle also works for correlated equilibria: for every arbitrary *coordinating device* a.k.a. correlating, there exists another direct device for which the state space equals the action space of each player.
[src:mechanism-design/revelation-principle] Then the coordination is done by directly informing each player of his action.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] A **Vickrey auction** or **sealed-bid second-price auction** (**SBSPA**) is a type of sealed-bid auction.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] Bidders submit written bids without knowing the bid of the other people in the auction.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] The highest bidder wins but the price paid is the second-highest bid.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] This type of auction is strategically similar to an English auction and gives bidders an incentive to bid their true value.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] The auction was first described academically by Columbia University professor William Vickrey in 1961 though it had been used by stamp collectors since 1893.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] In 1797 Johann Wolfgang von Goethe sold a manuscript using a sealed-bid, second-price auction.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] Vickrey's original paper mainly considered auctions where only a single, indivisible good is being sold.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] The terms *Vickrey auction* and *second-price sealed-bid auction* are, in this case only, equivalent and used interchangeably.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] In the case of multiple identical goods, the bidders submit inverse demand curves and pay the opportunity cost.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] Vickrey auctions are much studied in economic literature but uncommon in practice.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] Generalized variants of the Vickrey auction for multiunit auctions exist, such as the generalized second-price auction used in Google's and Yahoo!'s online advertisement programs (not incentive compatible) and the Vickrey–Clarke–Groves auction (incentive compatible).
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] In a Vickrey auction with private values each bidder maximizes their expected utility by bidding (revealing) their valuation of the item for sale.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] These types of auctions are sometimes used for specified pool trading in the agency mortgage-backed securities (MBS) market.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] The dominant strategy in a Vickrey auction with a single, indivisible item is for each bidder to bid their true value of the item.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] Let $v_{i}$ be bidder i's value for the item.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] Let $b_{i}$ be bidder $i{\text{'s}}$ bid for the item.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] The strategy of overbidding is dominated by bidding truthfully (i.e. bidding $v_{i}$ ).
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] Assume that bidder i bids $b_{i}>v_{i}$ .
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] Thus the strategy of bidding higher than one's true valuation is dominated by the strategy of truthfully bidding.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] The strategy of underbidding is also dominated by bidding truthfully.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] Assume that bidder i bids $b_{i}<v_{i}$ .
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] Thus the strategy of underbidding is dominated by the strategy of truthfully bidding.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] As truthful bidding dominates the other possible strategies (i.e. underbidding and overbidding), it is an optimal strategy.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] The two most common auctions are the sealed first price (or high-bid) auction and the open ascending price (or English) auction.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] In the former each buyer submits a sealed bid.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] The high bidder is awarded the item and pays his or her bid.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] In the latter, the auctioneer announces successively higher asking prices and continues until no one is willing to accept a higher price.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] Suppose that a buyer's valuation is v and the current asking price is b .
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] If $v<b$ , then the buyer loses by raising his hand.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] If $v>b$ and the buyer is not the current high bidder, it is more profitable to bid than to let someone else be the winner.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] Thus it is a dominant strategy for a buyer to drop out of the bidding when the asking price reaches his or her valuation.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] Thus, just as in the Vickrey sealed second price auction, the price paid by the buyer with the highest valuation is equal to the second highest value.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] Consider then the expected payment in the sealed second-price auction.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] Vickrey considered the case of two buyers and assumed that each buyer's value was an independent draw from a uniform distribution with support $[0,1]$ .
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] With buyers bidding according to their dominant strategies, a buyer with valuation v wins if his opponent's value $x<v$ .
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] That is, the payment of the winner in the sealed first-price auction is equal to the expected revenue in the sealed second-price auction.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] Suppose that buyer 2 bids according to the strategy $B(v)=v/2$ , where $B(v)$ is the buyer's bid for a valuation v .
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] We need to show that buyer 1's best response is to use the same strategy.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] Note first that if buyer 2 uses the strategy $B(v)=v/2$ , then buyer 2's maximum bid is $B(1)=1/2$ and so buyer 1 wins with probability 1 with any bid of 1/2 or more.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] Consider then a bid b on the interval $[0,1/2]$ .
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] Under Vickrey's assumption of uniformly distributed values, the win probability is $w(b)=2b$ .
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] Note that $U(b)$ takes on its maximum at $b=v/2=B(v)$ .
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] In network routing, VCG mechanisms are a family of payment schemes based on the added value concept.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] The basic idea of a VCG mechanism in network routing is to pay the owner of each link or node (depending on the network model) that is part of the solution, its declared cost *plus* its added value.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] In many routing problems, this mechanism is not only strategyproof, but also the minimum among all strategyproof mechanisms.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] where MCF(*G*) indicates the cost of the minimum-cost flow in graph *G* and *G* − *e**k* indicates graph *G* without the link *e**k*.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] This routing problem is one of the cases for which VCG is strategyproof and minimum.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] as *n*, approaches $\scriptstyle \infty$ , for $np=\omega ({\sqrt {n\log n}})$ .
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] The most obvious generalization to multiple or divisible goods is to have all winning bidders pay the amount of the highest non-winning bid.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] This is known as a uniform price auction.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] The uniform-price auction does not, however, result in bidders bidding their true valuations as they do in a second-price auction unless each bidder has demand for only a single unit.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] A generalization of the Vickrey auction that maintains the incentive to bid truthfully is known as the Vickrey–Clarke–Groves (VCG) mechanism.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] The idea in VCG is that items are assigned to maximize the sum of utilities; then each bidder pays the "opportunity cost" that their presence introduces to all the other players.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] This opportunity cost for a bidder is defined as the total bids of all the other bidders that would have won if the first bidder had not bid, minus the total bids of all the other actual winning bidders.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] A different kind of generalization is to set a reservation price—a minimum price below which the item is not sold at all.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] In some cases, setting a reservation price can substantially increase the revenue of the auctioneer.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] This is an example of Bayesian-optimal mechanism design.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-auction] In mechanism design, the revelation principle can be viewed as a generalization of the Vickrey auction.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] In mechanism design, the **Vickrey–Clarke–Groves** (**VCG**) **mechanism** is a generic truthful mechanism for achieving a socially optimal solution whenever monetary transfers are available.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] It generalizes the Vickrey–Clarke–Groves auction into a general-purpose mechanism for social choice, which can be used to select any outcome from a set of possible outcomes.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] However, the VCG mechanism also has several problems which keep it from fully solving the public goods problem, including its vulnerability to collusion and the issue of participants failing to pay their bids.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] There are n agents, each of which has a set of outcome valuations.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] which expresses the value it has for each alternative, in monetary terms.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] In other words, our social-choice function is utilitarian.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] The VCG family is a family of mechanisms that implements the utilitarian welfare function.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] Based on the agents' report-vector v , it calculates $x^{*}=x^{opt}(v)$ as above.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] where $v_{-i}=(v_{1},\dots ,v_{i-1},v_{i+1},\dots ,v_{n})$ , that is, $h_{i}$ is a function that depends only on the valuations of the other agents.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] Every mechanism in the VCG family is a truthful mechanism, that is, a mechanism where bidding the true valuation is a dominant strategy.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] The agent is paid the total value of the other agents; hence, together with its own value, the total welfare of the agent is exactly equal to the total welfare of society.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] Hence, the incentives of the agent are aligned with those of the society and the agent is incentivized to be truthful in order to help the mechanism achieve its goal.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] The function $h_{i}$ , in step 4, does not affect the agent's incentives, since it depends only on the declarations of the other agents.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] The function $h_{i}$ is a parameter of the mechanism.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] Every selection of $h_{i}$ yields a different mechanism in the VCG family.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] but then we would have to actually pay the players to participate in the auction.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] We would rather prefer that players give money to the mechanism.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] This is exactly the externality of player i .
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] This makes the VCG mechanism a win-win game: the players receive the outcomes they desire, and pay an amount which is less than their gain.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] So the players remain with a net positive gain, and the mechanism gains a net positive payment.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] where $w_{i}$ is a weight assigned to agent i .
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] The VCG mechanism can be adapted to situations in which the goal is to minimize the sum of costs (instead of maximizing the sum of gains).
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] Costs can be represented as negative values, so that minimization of cost is equivalent to maximization of values.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] The payments in step 3 are negative: each agent has to pay the total cost incurred by all other agents.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] If agents are free to choose whether to participate or not, then we must make sure that their net payment is non-negative (this requirement is called individual rationality).
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] The Clarke pivot rule can be used for this purpose: in step 4, each agent i is paid the total cost that would have been incurred by other agents, if the agent i would not participate.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] The net payment to agent i is its marginal contribution to reducing the total cost.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] The Vickrey–Clarke–Groves auction is a specific application of the VCG mechanism to the problem of selling goods.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] Here, X is the set of all possible allocations of items to the agents.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] Each agent assigns a personal monetary value to each bundle of items, and the goal is to maximize the sum of values for all agents.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] A well-known special case is the Vickrey auction, or the sealed second-bid auction.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] Here, there is only a single item, and the set X contains $n+1$ possible outcomes: either sell the item to one of the n agents, or not to sell it at all.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] In step 3, the winner agent is paid 0 (since the total value of the others is 0) and the losers receive a payment equal to the declared value of the winner.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] In step 4, the winner pays the second-highest bid (the total value of the others had he not participated) and the losers pay the declared value of the winner (the total value of the others had they not participated).
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] All in all, the winner pays the second-highest bid and the losers pay 0.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] A VCG mechanism can also be used in a double auction.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] It is the most general form of incentive-compatible double-auction since it can handle a combinatorial auction with arbitrary value functions on bundles.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] Unfortunately, it is not budget-balanced: the total value paid by the buyers is smaller than the total value received by the sellers.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] Hence, in order to make it work, the auctioneer has to subsidize the trade.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] The government wants to decide whether to undertake a certain project.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] Each citizen derives a different value from the project.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] The project should be undertaken if the sum of values of all citizens is more than the cost.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] Here, the VCG mechanism with the Clarke pivot rule means that a citizen pays a non-zero tax for that project if and only if they are pivotal, i.e., without their declaration the total value is less than *C* and with their declaration the total value is more than *C*.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] This taxing scheme is incentive-compatible, but again it is not budget-balanced – the total amount of tax collected is usually less than *C*.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] The **quickest path** problem is a cost-minimization problem.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] The goal is to send a message between two points in a communication network, which is modeled as a graph.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] Each computer in the network is modeled as an edge in the graph.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] Different computers have different transmission speeds, so every edge in the network has a numeric cost equal to the number of milliseconds it takes to transmit the message.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] Our goal is to send the message as quickly as possible, so we want to find the path with the smallest total cost.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] If we know the transmission-time of each computer (-the cost of each edge), then we can use a standard algorithm for solving the shortest path problem.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] If we do not know the transmission times, then we have to ask each computer to tell us its transmission-time.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] But, the computers have their own selfish interests so they might not tell us the truth.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] For example, a computer might tell us that its transmission time is very large, so that we will not bother it with our messages.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] The VCG mechanism can be used to solve this problem.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] Here, X is the set of all possible paths; the goal is to select a path $x\in X$ with minimal total cost.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] The value of an agent, $v_{i}(x)$ , is minus the time it spent on the message: it is negative if $i\in x$ and it is zero if $i\notin x$ .
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] The payment in step 3 is negative: each agent should pay to us the total time that the other agents spent on the message (note that the value is measured in units of time.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] We assume that it is possible to pay computers in units of time, or that it there is a standard way to translate time to money).
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] This means that, together with its own spent time, each agent actually loses the total time it took the message to arrive its destination, so the agent is incentivized to help the mechanism achieve the shortest transmission time.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] The Clarke pivot rule can be used to make the mechanism individually-rational: after paying us the cost, each agent receives from us a positive payment, which is equal to the time it would have taken the message to arrive at its destination if the agent would not have been present.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] Obviously, this time is weakly larger than the time required when the agent is present, so the net gain of every agent is weakly positive.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] Intuitively, each agent is paid according to its marginal contribution to the transmission.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] Other graph problems can be solved in a similar way, e.g. minimum spanning tree or maximum matching.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] A similar solution applies to the more general case where each agent holds some subset of the edges.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] For another example, where the VCG mechanism provides a sub-optimal approximation, see truthful job scheduling.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] A VCG mechanism implements a utilitarian social-choice function - a function that maximizes a weighted sum of values (also called an **affine maximizer**).
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] then *only* weighted utilitarian functions can be implemented.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] So with unrestricted valuations, the social-choice functions implemented by VCG mechanisms are the *only* functions that can be implemented truthfully.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] Moreover, the price-functions of the VCG mechanisms are also unique in the following sense.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] I.e, the price functions of the two mechanisms differ only by a function that does not depend on the agent's valuation $v_{i}$ (only on the valuations of the other agents).
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] This means that VCG mechanisms are the only truthful mechanisms that maximize the utilitarian social-welfare.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] A VCG mechanism has to calculate the optimal outcome, based on the agents' reports (step 2 above).
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] In some cases, this calculation is computationally difficult.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] For example, in combinatorial auctions, calculating the optimal assignment is NP-hard.
[src:mechanism-design/vickrey-clarke-groves-mechanism] Sometimes there are approximation algorithms to the optimization problem, but, using such an approximation might make the mechanism non-truthful.
